@NODE Introduction

@{B}Introduction@{UB}

  This is a no-nonsense, memory-lite program launcher.

  It adds items to your workbench TOOLS menu, which are set up using
a seperate configuration program.

  The tools can be launched with a workbench sytle environment,
or a cli environment.  They can optionally be launched with
selected icons as arguments.


  It is based on MicroTM, by Michal Kara.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Features

@{B}Features@{UB}

  ° Is a commodity
  ° Has a seperate prefs program
  ° Launches programs with either workbench or cli environments
  ° Configurable argument passing
  ° Removeable!
  ° Small! (less than 6k)

@ENDNODE

@NODE Requirements

@{B}System Requirements@{UB}

  EasyTM was developed on a KS3.1 A1200(AT).  I dont think I've used any
KS3 only function calls, so it should work on any machine with KickStart 2
or above.

  It also requires the excellent WBStart.Library 2.0, by Stefan Becker,
available on Aminet, or any good pd library.  Make sure you get the
library, and not the (old) Handler version.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Installation

@{B}Installation@{UB}

  Automagically : double click on the installer script.

  Manually :
	° Drag EasyTM to your WBStartUp drawer
	° Drag EasyTM-Prefs to your SYS:Prefs drawer
	° Start EasyTM-Prefs, and set some tools up, or load
	  the one provided.
	° (Optionally) Put the documentation somewhere sensible.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Configuration

@{B}Configuration@{UB}

  To run the configuration program, double click on its icon, or
use Exchange to show EasyTM's interface.


Gadgets
-------

  On the left hand side is a list view, which shows the menu items,
in the order they would appear in the tools menu.

  Below that is a string gadget which allows you to change how the
item appears in the menu.  Thus, the menu text can be different from
the actual program launched (eg "Display", or "Show Animation").

  Beneath that are four gadgets to create new items, delete old items,
and rearrange the order they appear in.


  On the right hand side are the properties of the menu items.

  First, there are the tool and directory gadgets. which allow you
to specify what program is to be launched.  Next to these is a gadget
which brings up a file requester to set these.

  Below that, are two integer gadgets which allow you to set the stack
size and task priority.  Each has an additional button to get this
information from the icon for that program.  Note, the stack must be
at least 4096 bytes.

  Next is a cycle gadget which switches between launching programs
with a workbench environment, or a cli environment.  CLI programs
will open a console if it generates output.  If you wish to
discard the output, add a ">NIL:" in the file gadget.

  Finally, there is cycle gadget which determines how arguments are
passed.  If NONE is selected, then no arguments will be passed to
the launched program.  If EACH is selected, then the program will be
starred once for each icon selected.  If ALL is selected, then
the program will be launched once, with all the icons as arguments.

  CLI programs need to have a "%s" inserted into the file gadget to
specify where to insert the arguments.  If you dont specify a "%s",
the program will be run with NO arguments.  If there are no icons
selected, then programs with EACH and ALL argument passing will not
be run.


Menus
-----

  Project->Open    : Load a config file from anywhere
  Project->Save As : Save the current tools list to a named file
  Project->About   : Brings up a requester about the prefs program
  Project->Quit    : Quits the prefs program without saving the list

  Edit->Defaults   : Clears the list
  Edit->Last Saved : Reloads the list from ENVARC:EasyTM.Config
  Edit->Restore    : Reloads the list from ENV:EasyTM.config

  Settings->Create icons: Determines whether an icon is created with the
     tools list file.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Bugs

@{B}Bugs@{UB}

  EasyTM:
	° Not very much error reporting. (i.e. none)

  EasyTM-Prefs:
	° Not very much error reporting. (i.e. sparse)
	° The "Create Icons?" menu item does NOTHING (yet)

@ENDNODE

@NODE Future

@{B}Future@{UB}

  "Looking at the future is like eating cake - you dont know what
